{
  "doc_id": "6915",
  "text": "Deep sequencing for transcriptomic studies (RNA-seq) generates more detailed data, including specific isoform, exon-specific transcript and allelic expression levels [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , mapping of transcription start sites, identification of sense and antisense transcripts, detection of alternative splicing events, and discovery of unannotated exons [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . To date, RNA-seq methods have been conducted in rheumatic disease studies of RA [CITATION_6] and SLE [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] , and in a murine model of inflammatory arthritis [CITATION_9] .",
